"# Chapter 11 — Java and managed runtimes

Java arrived in 1995. It changed how the industry thought about
programming languages by making 'managed' runtimes — with garbage
collection, no direct memory access, and portable bytecode — a
mainstream choice.

## The pitch

James Gosling and his team at Sun Microsystems were originally
building a language for set-top boxes and consumer electronics. When
the web arrived, they redirected the language toward web applets —
programs downloaded from a server and run in a browser.

The applets idea didn't last, but the language did. Sun's pitch:

- **Write once, run anywhere**. Java compiled to bytecode, and any
  machine with a Java Virtual Machine (JVM) could run that bytecode.
  You didn't need to recompile for different platforms.

- **Safer than C++**. No pointer arithmetic. No manual memory
  management (the runtime handled garbage collection). Runtime
  checks for array bounds, null pointers, etc. Type-safe.

- **Familiar syntax**. Java looked like C++, more or less. Curly
  braces, semicolons, class definitions. C++ programmers didn't have
  to learn a completely new syntax.

- **Rich standard library**. Java came with a huge library:
  collections, networking, threading, GUI, cryptography.

The pitch worked. Java grew enormously in the late 1990s and 2000s.

## The JVM

The Java Virtual Machine is a specification for a stack-based
virtual machine. Java compiles to JVM bytecode, and the JVM runs
that bytecode.

The JVM does several jobs:
- **Loading and linking** classes at runtime, so programs can be
  extended dynamically.
- **Verification** that bytecode is well-formed and type-safe.
- **Garbage collection** — reclaiming unused memory.
- **Just-in-time compilation** — translating hot bytecode to native
  machine code for speed. Modern JVMs (HotSpot, GraalVM) are among
  the most sophisticated JITs ever built.
- **Threading** and thread scheduling.

The JVM became so useful that other languages started targeting it.
Scala, Kotlin, Clojure (Chapter 4), Groovy, JRuby — all compile to
JVM bytecode. The JVM ecosystem is enormous.

## What managed runtimes do

A 'managed' runtime is one that handles memory automatically and
enforces safety rules the language couldn't otherwise guarantee.

Managed runtimes typically provide:
- **Garbage collection**: memory that's no longer reachable is
  reclaimed automatically. No `malloc/free` bugs.
- **Bounds checking**: array accesses check whether the index is
  in range.
- **Null safety** (in newer designs): the language distinguishes
  values that might be null from those that can't.
- **Type safety**: values don't get reinterpreted as different types.
- **Dynamic loading**: code can be loaded and unloaded at runtime.

The cost: some runtime overhead. A managed runtime is slower than
hand-tuned C for the same task. In exchange you get memory safety,
easier programming, and portability.

## Garbage collection

The critical feature of most managed runtimes. The idea: instead of
the programmer explicitly freeing memory when done with it, the
runtime tracks what's still reachable and reclaims the rest.

Classic GC algorithms:
- **Reference counting**: every object counts how many references
  point at it. When the count drops to zero, free the memory. Simple
  but can't handle cycles.
- **Mark-and-sweep**: periodically walk from known roots, mark
  reachable objects, sweep the rest into a free list.
- **Copying**: split memory in half. Copy live objects from one half
  to the other, then swap halves.
- **Generational**: exploit the observation that most objects die
  young. Collect young objects frequently; collect older objects
  less often.

Modern GCs are sophisticated. G1, ZGC, Shenandoah on the JVM. Real-
time GCs that guarantee bounded pauses. GCs that run concurrently
with the mutator.

Lisp had garbage collection from the beginning (1958). Every serious
Lisp implementation has some kind of GC. The Java era popularized GC
outside the Lisp world.

## .NET / CLR

Microsoft's answer to Java was .NET, first released in 2002. The
Common Language Runtime (CLR) plays a role similar to the JVM — a
managed runtime with garbage collection, JIT compilation, and rich
libraries.

.NET was designed to support multiple languages targeting the same
runtime from the start. C# is the primary language. F# (functional),
VB.NET (Visual Basic descendant), and others also target the CLR.

.NET was Windows-only for years but is now cross-platform (.NET
Core, later just .NET, running on Linux, macOS, and Windows).

## What Motoi's runtime looks like

Motoi Scheme's runtime is a managed runtime in its own small way.
It has:
- **Garbage collection**: Motoi's memory is managed by the host
  JavaScript engine (V8, SpiderMonkey, or similar), which has a
  garbage collector.
- **Type safety**: Motoi values carry runtime type tags. The
  interpreter checks them.
- **Dynamic loading**: carts can be added to the runtime after it
  starts.

Motoi is written in JavaScript. JavaScript itself runs in a managed
runtime with GC, bounds checking, and JIT compilation. So Motoi
inherits managed-runtime properties by construction.

## The 'sufficiently smart compiler' problem

For decades, computer science had a running joke about the
'sufficiently smart compiler' — a hypothetical compiler that could
make any high-level language as fast as C.

Modern JIT compilers get closer to this than the joke suggested was
possible. HotSpot, V8, PyPy, and others perform speculative
optimizations at runtime based on the code's actual behavior. Hot
Java code often runs at speeds comparable to C.

The tradeoff: startup latency (the JIT needs to see hot code before
it optimizes) and memory usage (JIT compilers keep multiple
versions of methods around). For long-running server processes,
this is fine. For command-line tools that need to start fast, less
so.

## What Motoi wants you to take from this

Managed runtimes shifted the industry. Most professional software
today runs on a managed runtime — Java, .NET, JavaScript, Python,
Ruby, Go's runtime (which has some managed features).

The tradeoff — some runtime overhead for a lot of safety and
convenience — has been generally accepted for most applications.
Where you need bare-metal speed (games, kernels, embedded, some
scientific computing), C, C++, and Rust still rule. Where you need
programmer productivity, managed runtimes rule.

Motoi Scheme runs on top of a managed runtime (JavaScript). Motoi is
tiny compared to the JVM or .NET. But the same design tradeoffs
apply — safer, slower than raw C, easier to program in.")
